[src:thymeleaf/documentation] Quick glimpses into what Thymeleaf can bring to your project.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] To deploy and run Jakarta Server Pages, a compatible web server with a servlet container, such as Apache Tomcat or Jetty, is required.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Architecturally, JSP may be viewed as a high-level abstraction of Jakarta Servlets.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] JSPs are translated into servlets at runtime, therefore JSP is a Servlet; each JSP servlet is cached and re-used until the original JSP is modified.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Jakarta Server Pages can be used independently or as the view component of a server-side model–view–controller design, normally with JavaBeans as the model and Java servlets (or a framework such as Apache Struts) as the controller.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] JSP allows Java code and certain predefined actions to be interleaved with static web markup content, such as HTML.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The resulting page is compiled and executed on the server to deliver a document.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The compiled pages, as well as any dependent Java libraries, contain Java bytecode rather than machine code.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Like any other .jar or Java program, code must be executed within a Java virtual machine (JVM) that interacts with the server's host operating system to provide an abstract, platform-neutral environment.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] JSPs are usually used to deliver HTML and XML documents, but through the use of OutputStream, they can deliver other types of data as well.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The Web container creates JSP implicit objects like request, response, session, application, config, page, pageContext, out and exception.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] JSP Engine creates these objects during translation phase.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] JSPs use several delimiters for scripting functions.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The most basic is `<% ... %>`, which encloses a JSP *scriptlet.* A scriptlet is a fragment of Java code that runs when the user requests the page.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Other common delimiters include `<%= ... %>` for *expressions,* where the scriptlet and delimiters are replaced with the result of evaluating the expression, and *directives*, denoted with `<%@ ... %>`.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Java code is not required to be complete or self-contained within a single scriptlet block.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] It can straddle markup content, provided that the page as a whole is syntactically correct.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] For example, any Java *if/for/while* blocks opened in one scriptlet must be correctly closed in a later scriptlet for the page to successfully compile.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] This allows code to be intermingled and can result in poor programming practices.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Content that falls inside a split block of Java code (spanning multiple scriptlets) is subject to that code.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Content inside an *if* block will only appear in the output when the *if* condition evaluates to true.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Likewise, content inside a loop construct may appear multiple times in the output, depending upon how many times the loop body runs.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The JSP `useBean` tag enables the developer to access and create a Javabean.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Although using the `useBean` tag looks similar to an HTML tag, all JSP tags for JavaBeans use XML syntax.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Therefore the code containing the `useBean` tag is case-sensitive.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The `useBean` tag contains several attributes.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The `id` attribute declares the name that is used for gaining access to the bean.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The `class` attribute declares the package and class for the bean.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The `scope` declares the object responsible for storing the bean.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The value for the scope defines the duration for which the bean is available for the rest of the java application to use.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] After a bean has been created using the `useBean` tag, the `getProperty` and `setProperty` tags can be used for getting and setting the properties of the bean.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The JSP `getProperty` is used to get the property of created bean.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The JSP `setProperty` tag is used to set the properties for a bean.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] For the `getProperty` and `setProperty` tags, the name attribute is used to specify the bean's name.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] So the name attribute must match the id attribute provided by the `useBean` tag.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Version 2.0 of the JSP specification added support for the Expression Language (EL), used to access data and functions in Java objects.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] In JSP 2.1, it was folded into the Unified Expression Language, which is also used in JavaServer Faces.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The JSP Expression Language uses a compact syntax which enables the developer to get attributes and JavaBean properties from a given request object.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] When using EL, a dollar sign ("$") must be added at the beginning of the code.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The dollar symbol is followed by an opening brace ("{"), as well as a closing brace ("}").
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The code is then written between the opening and closing braces.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The value of `variable` in the object `javabean` is `${javabean.variable}`.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] The JSP syntax adds additional tags, called JSP actions, to invoke built-in functionality.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Additionally, the technology allows for the creation of custom JSP *tag libraries* that act as extensions to the standard JSP syntax.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Jakarta Standard Tag Library (JSTL) supports common tasks that must be performed in JSPs.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Examples includes iteration and conditionals (the equivalent of "for" and "if" statements in Java).
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Out of all the libraries in JSTL, the JSTL core library is most commonly used.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] A taglib directive must be used to specify the URI of the JSTL core library using a prefix.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Although there are many different choices for the prefix, the "c" prefix is commonly used for this library.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] JSP pages may also be written in fully valid XML syntax.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Such JSP files commonly use the alternative `.jspx` file extension, which usually causes the application server to validate the XML syntax.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Since the usual JSP syntax `<% ... %>` is not valid in XML, a developer must use alternative tags provided by JSP.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] For example, the common `<%@ page .. %>` directive may instead be written as a `<jsp:directive.page .. />` tag, and tag libraries are imported using XML namespaces, instead of the usual `<%@ taglib .. %>` tag.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] A **JavaServer Pages compiler** is a program that parses JSPs and transforms them into executable Java Servlets.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] A program of this type is usually embedded into the application server and run automatically the first time a JSP is accessed, but pages may also be precompiled for better performance, or compiled as a part of the build process to test for errors.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Some JSP containers support configuring how often the container checks JSP file timestamps to see whether the page has changed.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Typically, this timestamp would be set to a short interval (perhaps seconds) during software development, and a longer interval (perhaps minutes, or even never) for a deployed Web application.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] According to Joel Murach and Michael Urban, authors of the book "Murach's Java Servlets and JSP", embedding Java code in JSP is generally bad practice.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] A better approach would be to migrate the back-end logic embedded in the JSP to the Java code in the `Servlet`.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] In this scenario, the `Servlet` is responsible for processing, and the JSP is responsible for displaying the HTML, maintaining a clear separation of concerns.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] In 2000, Jason Hunter, author of "Java Servlet Programming" described a number of "problems" with JavaServer Pages.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Nevertheless, he wrote that while JSP may not be the "best solution for the Java Platform" it was the "Java solution that is most like the non-Java solution," by which he meant Microsoft's Active Server Pages.
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Later, he added a note to his site saying that JSP had improved since 2000, but also cited its competitors, Apache Velocity and Tea (template language).
[src:thymeleaf/javaserver-pages] Today, several alternatives and a number of JSP-oriented pages in larger web apps are considered to be technical debt.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] A **template processor** (also known as a **template engine** or **template parser**) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] The language that the templates are written in is known as a **template language** or **templating language**.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] For purposes of this article, a result document is any kind of formatted output, including documents, web pages, or source code (in source code generation), either in whole or in fragments.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] A template engine is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework, and may be used also as a preprocessor or filter.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] Template engines typically include features common to most high-level programming languages, with an emphasis on features for processing plain text.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] The templating languages are generally simple substitution-only languages, in contrast to the more sophisticated facilities in full-blown template processors, but may contain some logic.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] Simple examples include ‘printf’ print format strings, found in many programming languages, and snippets, found in a number of text editors and source code editors.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] In word processors, templates are a common feature, while automatic filling in of the templates is often referred to as mail merge.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] An illustrative example of the complementary nature of parsing and templating is the `s` (substitute) command in the sed text processor, originating from search-and-replace in the ed text editor.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] For example, `s/(cat|dog)s?/\1s/g` replaces all occurrences of "cat" or "dog" with "cats" or "dogs", without duplicating an existing "s": `(cat|dog)` is the 1st (and only) sub-expression in the regexp, and `\1` in the format string substitutes this into the output.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] This may be a relational database, a source file such as XML, an alternate format of flat file database, a spreadsheet or any of other various sources of preformatted data.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] Some template processing systems are limited in the types of data that can be used.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] Others are designed for maximum flexibility and allow many different types of data.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] Additionally some template engines allow additional configuration options.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] These may consist of an entire document or a document fragment.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] Template processing is used in various contexts for different purposes.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] The specific purpose is ordinarily contingent upon the software application or template engine in use.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] However, the flexibility of template processing systems often enables unconventional uses for purposes not originally intended by the original designers.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] A **template engine** is a specific kind of template processing module that exhibits all of the major features of a modern programming language.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] The term *template engine* evolved as a generalized description of programming languages whose primary or exclusive purpose was to process templates and data to output text.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] The use of this term is most notably applied to web development using a web template system, and it is also applied to other contexts as well.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] Document generation frameworks typically use template processing as the central model for generating documents.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] A web template engine processes web templates and source data (typically from a relational database) to produce one or more output web pages or page fragments.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] It is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] Currently, template processing software is most frequently used in the context of development for the web.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] XSLT is a template processing model designed by W3C.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] It is designed primarily for transformations on XML data (into web documents or other output).
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] Programming languages such as Perl, Python, PHP, Ruby, C#, Java, and Go support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] JavaServer Pages, Active Server Pages, Genshi (for Python), and eRuby are examples of template engines designed specifically for web application development.
[src:thymeleaf/template-processor] Moreover, template processing is sometimes included as a sub-feature of software packages like text editors, IDEs and relational database management systems.
[src:thymeleaf/thymeleaf] In web applications Thymeleaf aims to be a complete substitute for JavaServer Pages (JSP), and implements the concept of *Natural Templates*: template files that can be directly opened in browsers and that still display correctly as web pages.
[src:thymeleaf/thymeleaf] Thymeleaf is open-source software, licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:thymeleaf/thymeleaf] The following example produces an HTML5 table with rows for each item of a *List<Product>* variable called *allProducts*.
[src:thymeleaf/thymeleaf] Also, this fragment of (X)HTML code can be perfectly displayed by a browser as a prototype, without being processed at all: it is a *natural template*.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] A **web template system** in web publishing allows web designers and developers to work with *web templates* to automatically generate custom web pages, such as the results from a search.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] This reuses static web page elements while defining dynamic elements based on web request parameters.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Web templates support static content, providing basic structure and appearance.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Developers can implement templates from content management systems, web application frameworks, and HTML editors.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] The template and content resources are processed and combined by the template engine to mass-produce web documents, each with a similar visual format.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, web documents include any of various output formats for transmission over the web via HTTP, HTTPS, or another Internet protocol.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] A template processor (also known as a template engine or template parser) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] The language that the templates are written in is known as a template language or templating language.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] With the model typically held in a relational database, the remaining components of the MVC architecture are the control and view.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] In the simplest of systems these two are not separated.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] However, adapting the separation of concerns principle one can completely decouple the relationships.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] A web browser and web server are a client–server architecture.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Sites often also use a web cache to improve performance.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] In many implementations, template files contain variables or placeholders that are replaced with data supplied by an application when the page is generated.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] The source code of the template engine can be proprietary or open source.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Many template systems are a component of a larger programming platform or framework.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] They are referred to as the "platform's template system".
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Some template systems have the option of substituting a different template language or engine.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Programming languages such as Perl, Ruby, C, and Java support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] JavaServer Pages (JSP), PHP, and Active Server Pages (ASP with VBScript, JScript or other languages) are examples, themselves, of web template engines.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] These technologies are typically used in server-side templating systems, but could be adapted for use on an "edge-side" proxy or for static page generation.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Static site generators are engines that use flat text input files like markdown and asciidoc to generate a static web page.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Examples of this include Jekyll (Liquid, Ruby), Hugo (Go templates), and Pelican (Jinja2, Python).
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Some hosted website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, provide template-based systems that allow users to create static and dynamic web pages through graphical user interfaces rather than traditional programming.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] HTML editors often use web template systems to produce only static web pages.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] These can be viewed as a ready-made web design, used to mass-produce "cookie-cutter" websites for rapid deployment.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] They also commonly include themes in place of CSS styles.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] In general, the template language is used only with the editor's software.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] FrontPage and Dreamweaver were once the most popular editors with template sub-systems.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] A Flash web template uses Macromedia Flash to create visually interactive sites.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Many *server-side template systems* have an option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] This is common on content management systems, like Vignette, but is not considered out-server generation.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] In the majority of cases, this "publish option" doesn't interfere with the *template system*, and it can be made by external software, as Wget.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existent software adapted for this task.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for the web use, running on CGI.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, started with SSI.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Technically, the methodology of embedding programming languages within HTML (or XML, etc.), used in many "server-side included script languages" are also templates.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] All of them are Embedded complex languages.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] There are also preprocessors used as server-side template engines.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] As for edge-side template and inclusion systems, "edge-side" refers to web servers that reside in the space between the client (browser) and the originating server.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] They are often referred to as "reverse-proxy" servers.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] These servers are generally tasked with reducing the load and traffic on originating servers by caching content such as images and page fragments, and delivering this to the browser in an efficient manner.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Basic Edge Side Includes (ESI) is an SSI-like language.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] ESI has been implemented for content delivery networks.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] The ESI template language may also be implemented in web browsers using JavaScript and Ajax, or via a browser "plug-in".
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] Many web browsers can apply an XSLT stylesheet to XML data that transforms the data into an XHTML document, thereby providing template functionality in the browser itself.
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] The most simple form is transclusions (HTML frames).
[src:thymeleaf/web-template-system] In other cases dynamic web pages are needed.
